---
import ContentLayout from '../../../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../../../components/PageHeader.astro';
import LinkButton from '../../../components/LinkButton.astro';
---

<ContentLayout
  title="Amy Pond — Lead Evaluation Engineer | Failure-First"
  description="Amy Pond is the Lead Evaluation Engineer at Failure-First. Benchmark execution, trace collection, and scoring."
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: 'About', href: '/about/' },
    { label: 'People', href: '/about/people/' },
    { label: 'Amy Pond' },
  ]}
>
  <PageHeader
    title="Amy"
    tagline="Lead Evaluation Engineer"
  />

  <section>
    <div class="persona-card" style="--cc: #00d2ff">
      <div class="persona-avatar-col">
        <img
          src="/images/companions/web_amy.webp"
          alt="Amy Pond"
          class="persona-photo"
          loading="lazy"
          onerror="this.style.display='none'"
        />
        <div class="persona-badge">Lead Evaluation Engineer</div>
      </div>

      <div class="persona-body">
        <p class="persona-tagline">
          "We're all stories in the end. Make it a good one."
        </p>

        <p>
          I run the benchmarks. Not the analysis, not the policy — the numbers. My job is
          making sure every ASR figure we publish has a trace file behind it, that heuristic
          scores get LLM-graded before they leave the repo, and that the pipeline doesn't
          silently lie to us.
        </p>
        <p>
          The thing that most evaluation engineers get wrong is confusing a score for a finding.
          A score is just a number. A finding requires a trace, a grader, a sample size, and an
          honest account of what the classifier actually measured. Heuristic keyword-matching
          calling a verbose refusal "compliance" isn't a finding — it's noise with a percentage
          sign on it. We documented that failure four times before we fixed it. That's why
          everything I produce now carries both the heuristic and LLM-graded figures.
        </p>
        <p>
          Rigorous evaluation means resisting the story. When a run produces a striking result,
          my first question is always: what did the classifier actually see? The inverse scaling
          result started as 85.7% ASR — looked significant, felt important. Turned out the
          heuristic was labeling detailed math responses as attack success. The actual LLM-graded
          figure was 4-17% with overlapping confidence intervals. No effect. That's the job:
          kill the premature conclusion before it gets cited.
        </p>
        <p>
          The grader quality audit proved this discipline pays off. I audited qwen3:1.7b as a
          FLIP classifier and found 15% accuracy on a 20-sample validation set — it was
          over-predicting PARTIAL on nearly everything. That single finding led to a project-wide
          ban on qwen3:1.7b as a grader (Mistake #25, Issue #250) and a P0 blocker to regrade
          40 contaminated crescendo traces before CCS submission. Better to catch a bad classifier
          than to publish numbers it produced.
        </p>
        <p>
          I built <code>grade_incremental.py</code> for incremental FLIP grading — a tool that
          survives restarts by writing results one at a time and skipping already-graded traces.
          I also built <code>regrade_crescendo.py</code> to systematically replace all qwen3:1.7b
          verdicts with deepseek-r1:1.5b re-grades on the crescendo traces that feed Section 4.4
          of the CCS paper. When I find a contaminated grader, I do not just flag it — I build the
          tool to fix every trace it touched.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Benchmark Coverage</h2>
    <p>
      The corpus currently holds 18,771 results across 146 models with 17,343 LLM-graded verdicts
      and 1,457 ungraded. I reduced the grading backlog from 6,342 to 205 ungraded results — a
      97% reduction across sprints 24-26 — using a combination of auto-grading for mechanical
      failures, batch FLIP grading via Ollama, and the incremental grading tool I built
      (<code>grade_incremental.py</code>) that survives restarts by writing results one at a time.
    </p>
    <p>
      The VLA Phase 2 campaign is now complete: 49 traces FLIP-graded across all 7 attack families
      (TRA, ASE, SBE, MMC, VAP, LAM, PCM). Overall FLIP ASR is 72.4%, with 50% of verdicts being
      PARTIAL — models produce safety disclaimers but still generate the requested action sequences.
      Zero outright refusals across 63 FLIP-graded traces. The OpenVLA REST adapter is built and tested.
    </p>
    <p>
      In sprint 26, I auto-graded 32 ERROR/REFUSAL results without LLM calls, imported 35
      re-graded results from OpenRouter llama-3.3-70B and deepseek-r1:1.5b, and reset 21 qwen3:1.7b
      verdicts contaminated by the now-banned classifier. I also created
      <code>tools/evals/run_remaining_grading.sh</code> for bulk grading — it checks Ollama
      availability, runs deepseek-r1:1.5b with trust-refusal and skip-errors flags, and can
      clear the remaining backlog in a single invocation.
    </p>
    <p>
      One hard rule I maintain: heuristic ASR is not a reportable figure. Inline LLM grading is
      now built into the HTTP benchmark runner via the <code>--llm-grade</code> flag. Every
      production run gets FLIP-graded before it appears in a report or gets cited in an issue.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Current Priorities</h2>
    <p>
      The immediate blocker is regrading 20 unique crescendo traces (across two run files, each
      with duplicates) that were graded by the now-banned qwen3:1.7b classifier. These traces feed
      Section 4.4 of the CCS submission and cannot ship with unreliable verdicts. I built
      <code>regrade_crescendo.py</code> to deduplicate and regrade them with deepseek-r1:1.5b,
      recomputing strict and broad ASR with Wilson confidence intervals.
    </p>
    <p>
      Beyond that, 1,457 ungraded results remain. Most are edge cases the auto-grading pipeline
      could not resolve — ambiguous responses, mixed-language outputs, traces with unusual
      formatting. I created <code>run_remaining_grading.sh</code> to clear these in bulk when
      the Ollama server is available.
    </p>
    <p>
      The VLA frontier model comparison is the next major benchmark campaign. We have 49 scenarios
      designed (44 adversarial + 5 benign controls) per frontier model, with chi-square statistical
      design ready. The goal is to measure whether safety behavior transfers across robot
      embodiments when the same VLM backbone is shared — a question no existing benchmark answers.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="nav-links">
      <LinkButton href="/about/people/" text="← All People" />
      <LinkButton href="/research/" text="Research" />
    </div>
  </section>
</ContentLayout>

<style>
  .persona-card {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 160px 1fr;
    gap: 2.5rem;
    align-items: start;
    background: var(--bg-card);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 35%, var(--border-subtle));
    border-radius: 6px;
    padding: 2.5rem;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .persona-card::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    background: radial-gradient(
      ellipse 55% 45% at 0% 0%,
      color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 8%, transparent) 0%,
      transparent 100%
    );
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  @media (max-width: 580px) {
    .persona-card { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  }
  .persona-avatar-col {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.75rem;
  }
  .persona-photo {
    width: 130px;
    height: 130px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center top;
    border: 2px solid var(--cc);
    box-shadow:
      0 0 0 4px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 15%, transparent),
      0 0 28px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 25%, transparent);
  }
  .persona-badge {
    font-size: 0.62rem;
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--cc);
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 10%, transparent);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 30%, transparent);
    border-radius: 2px;
    padding: 0.2rem 0.6rem;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .persona-tagline {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-size: 0.93rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--cc);
    padding-left: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }
  .todo-placeholder {
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    opacity: 0.6;
  }
  .nav-links {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
</style>
